item.title: Ess Hook (a.k.a. "s" hook)
item.description:
I needed some ess hooks...

I prefer serif fonts, so I went with Times New Roman. It's free to use, right?

In case you prefer Arial or something, I've included the Openscad file.

Printing:

  • No supports.
  • Make it strong, right? I added extra top and bottom layers, bumped up the infill.
  • Raft? At first it didn't stick so I was tempted. But as I find usually works, printing it hotter solved my problem.
  • These are about three inches tall; you can resize it as needed in your slicing program.

I find ess (s) to be the best letter for a hook.

Are any other letters useful? Perhaps jay, gee and lower case cue (j,g,q)?

Enjoy!

item.title: Tolerance Test (internal distances)
item.description: This is a test I threw together for a print-in-place project I am working on. It stands 1 inch tall and about 2.5 inches wide. At 20% infill and 65mm/s, this takes about 4.5 hours. It features a range of internal spacings and features arms to help free prints if need be, except for the middle which should just spin freely. This test also has .008in chamfers on the bottom edges to help with elephants' foot. Tests like these are crucial to gauge your prints for print-in-place parts with small distances

item.title: GM Points Cam Lubricator Delco 1852935 '62-'74
item.description:
Created for a friend who is rebuilding an old car and wanted to know if I could make this little plastic part. Apparently, the original part number is Delco-Remy 1852935

It fits inside an ignition distributor on many old GM cars common through the 1960's and early 1970s. It holds an oil soaked felt wick in close proximity to the distributor cam and fits into the small rectangular hole, pictured. The rare and fragile original I modeled this from is on the right, the black ASA printed replica is on the left.

As the distributor gets hot during operation, you probably want to print it in ABS, ASA, PolyCarbonate (PC) or Nylon. It is oriented for easiest printing with supports.

item.title: Decor Tellfresh Label replica
item.description:
These are a simple label that clips into the front of the Decor Tellfresh containers, and are an exact(ish) replica of the original.

You can write on them with pencil, then wipe off to re-use.

I printed these in PLA, but would probably be better in PETG (I had no white PETG on hand). If you want to get fancy, then upload into your favourite 3D modelling software and add a raised layer with common ingredient names, then 2 colour print…

For a smoother surface I also turned on Ironing in Prusa Slicer.

In the photos the yellow one is the original from Decor.

item.title: TooButton 3D Print Controller
item.description:
The TooButton, is a wireless controller for 3D printers. It provides fast direct commands when you need them. Click, Double Click, Press and Hold functionality can easitly be mapped to each key on the controller.

The TooButton can be mounted to your printer, or operated from a remote location.

Sends commands and custom G-code directly over your wireless network. TooButton also can gracefully shut down your Raspberry PI, and power on TP-Link Smart plugs for seamless automation.

item.title: Kyoketsu-Shoge Ninja Chain Weapon TMNT Scale
item.description:
I got inspired to make this after rewatching the first season of Daredevil and finding myself eager to have a Kyoketsu-Shoge like Nobu had, in the scale of my TMNT figures.

I took the design of the nunchucks that p7aymak3r made and essentially copy-and-pasted the chain part to make it longer, then whipped up the basic blade design. While the chain links might look flimsy they printed very well, simply needing a little effort to remove the support pieces.

item.title: AA to C battery converter
item.description:
Inspired by enif's Yet Another AA to C Battery Adapter (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1719966).

This is a sleeve that fits over a AA battery to give it the thickness of a C battery. I use them to fit NiMH rechargeables in things that usually require C batteries.

The centre slot for the AA is a touch tight at 14mm, and the outer edge is 24mm wide. The sleeve is designed to stretch over the AA battery for a snug fit, and the sleeve stretches to about 25mm when the battery is inserted.

Total height is 48mm, sleeving over the main body of the AA and allowing the positive end to protrude.

Direction inserted doesn't matter, it's the same at both ends. Minimalist but decently sturdy design that saves on plastic.

item.title: SV01 E3D Titan Extruder Stepper Mount (4mm offset)
item.description: This is a mount for the extruder stepper motor to offset the distance for a genuine E3D extruder to be mounted on a Sovol SV01 (could also work with other Sovol models but have not tested). This places the large gear nearly in the middle of the cutout on the stock bracket as seen in the pictures. This allows the user to use any stock orientation parts with the E3D extruder, or also allows the use of a E3D Extruder and V6 hotend combo which is the setup seen in the pictures. I printed this in PETG for strength and flexibility but could be printed with PLA as well.

item.title: knuckle buster
item.description:
this is a project im working on for fun its a 9 function joystick for pc
i wanted to design a non traditional joystick which the hand naturally integrated with

i was playing an online battle game using the mouse and keypad for control and i kept pushing the wrong key when things heated up
so i decided i wanted a simpler way to control and fire using a simple 5 button controller
4 direction and 1 fire button .the other function in the game will be added using magnetic
switches mounted under the controller so in all it will have10 function buttons
every thing can be controlled using one hand if this works out it should increase my reaction time
the controller itself is comprised of 2 parts. The micro switches were purchased on amazon
i designed a base to house my magnetic switches which will be activated when i move the controller over them by a magnet placed under the bottom i believe when done this will be a novel and fun way to play games ,once your muscle memory kicks in movement in game play should be pretty fluid .As the project progresses i will add the rest of the design along with parts list
